Project Description
Arduino-Based Agricultural Weed Remover Cart

The Arduino-Based Agricultural Weed Remover Cart is a smart farming prototype designed to automate the process of weed removal in agricultural fields. Weeds compete with crops for nutrients, water, and sunlight, reducing crop yield and requiring significant manual labor to remove. This project addresses that challenge by using an Arduino-controlled robotic cart equipped with a front-mounted weed-removing mechanism.

The cart is powered by DC geared motors and controlled through an Arduino microcontroller, which manages the movement and operation of the weed-removing mechanism. The prototype is designed to move between crop rows, helping farmers remove unwanted weeds efficiently while minimizing the use of chemical herbicides. Its lightweight and low-cost design makes it suitable as a proof-of-concept for small-scale farms and educational research.

This project demonstrates the practical application of embedded systems, robotics, and automation in agriculture. It provides a foundation for future enhancements such as AI-based weed detection, IoT-enabled remote monitoring, GPS navigation, obstacle avoidance, and solar-powered operation, making it a scalable solution for modern precision farming.

Key Objectives
Automate the weed removal process to reduce manual labor.
Improve agricultural productivity through smart farming techniques.
Minimize the use of chemical herbicides for environmentally friendly farming.
Develop a low-cost, efficient, and scalable agricultural robotic system.
Demonstrate the use of Arduino-based embedded systems in real-world agricultural applications.
Technologies Used
Arduino Uno
Embedded C (Arduino IDE)
L298N Motor Driver
DC Geared Motors
Servo Motor (for weed-removing mechanism)
Battery Power Supply
Robotic Chassis and Wheels

This project highlights the potential of integrating robotics and embedded systems into agriculture, offering an affordable and innovative approach to sustainable farming.
